              <span id="reviewTextContainer58044637" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer4704875300104839741">Well i just loved this book, not because it seems to be the definitive work on the civil war, a great bibliography, superb footnotes and fantastic anecdotes, but this kind of stuff is just really fascinating to me. I think for its time (1950&apos;s), it is very well researched and just really compacted with relevant data and story lines. Caton follows the Army of the potomac from the end of the first battle at Manasses to the end of Antietem and McClellans end.<br/><br/>&quot;Antietem was just a disparaging success</span>
  <span id="freeText4704875300104839741" style="display:none">Well i just loved this book, not because it seems to be the definitive work on the civil war, a great bibliography, superb footnotes and fantastic anecdotes, but this kind of stuff is just really fascinating to me. I think for its time (1950's), it is very well researched and just really compacted with relevant data and story lines. Caton follows the Army of the potomac from the end of the first battle at Manasses to the end of Antietem and McClellans end.<br /><br />"Antietem was just a disparaging succession of missed opportunities". Catton has a flair for understatement. I did have to read this book with an Atlas, but that's the way it is.<br /><br />I can't wait for Volumes II and III to find out who wins.</span>
  <a data-text-id="4704875300104839741" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
