    <div class="section">
      

<div id="review_4049369869" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/4049369869" />
    <a title="Leew49" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/8448607-leew49"><img alt="Leew49" src="https://s.gr-assets.com/assets/nophoto/user/u_50x66-632230dc9882b4352d753eedf9396530.png" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/4049369869?book_show_action=true">Jun 12, 2021</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Leew49" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Leew49" href="/user/show/8448607-leew49">Leew49</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

          <div class="uitext greyText bookshelves">
            Shelves:
              <a class="actionLinkLite" href="/review/list/8448607-leew49?shelf=history">history</a>
          </div>
    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer4049369869" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer8134980866329431246">This first book in Catton&apos;s Civil War trilogy begins with the 2nd Battle of Bull Run and ends with Antietam and the Emancipation Proclamation. Thus, it bookends the leadership period of George McClellan, providing fresh insight into the character of one of that period&apos;s more controversial figures. &quot;Little Mac&quot; was, in the hackneyed phrase, a study in contrasts: an inspiring and beloved military leader, he could be arrogant and dismissive to the politicians who had ultimate control over his caree</span>
  <span id="freeText8134980866329431246" style="display:none">This first book in Catton's Civil War trilogy begins with the 2nd Battle of Bull Run and ends with Antietam and the Emancipation Proclamation. Thus, it bookends the leadership period of George McClellan, providing fresh insight into the character of one of that period's more controversial figures. "Little Mac" was, in the hackneyed phrase, a study in contrasts: an inspiring and beloved military leader, he could be arrogant and dismissive to the politicians who had ultimate control over his career. Boastful and self-consciously heroic, he was overly cautious in moments when quick and ruthless decisiveness were called for. <br /><br />Even casual students of the Civil War are familiar with McClellan's famous snubbing of Lincoln, leaving the visiting President sitting in his parlor while the General retired for the night without acknowledging his presence. Catton gives us a different perspective: McClellan, and every general who led the Army of the Potomac had to deal with politicians of every stripe, from cabinet members like Stanton and Chase, who thought the cabinet should have more say in military strategy, to the Bipartisan Committee on the Conduct of the War, to Radical Republicans in Congress, who, if they had their way, would have used the litmus test of enthusiastic abolitionism as the principal criterion of worthy military leadership. In this hysterical political climate exhaustion and exasperation were both understandable on McClellan's part, though his lack of diplomacy certainly didn't help his cause.<br /><br />But McClellan's mediocre generalship on the battlefield was key to his undoing. Though a brilliant organizer who whipped the army into shape and inspired its men, McClellan was overly cautious and painstakingly deliberate in nature--traits which were magnified by his unfortunate use of Allan Pinkerton for military intelligence. Pinkerton, the founder of the eponymous detective agency, routinely overestimated Confederate strength, feeding into McClellan's obsessive need for caution, over-preparation, and delay. Consequently, the Peninsula Campaign was unsuccessful, and the battle of Antietam--for which McClellan had a huge military advantage--ended in a stalemate. The chance to destroy Lee's army was squandered, McClellan was replaced with Burnside, and the war dragged on for three more years. <br /><br />Catton relies heavily on the diaries, letters, and comments of enlisted men, and his appreciation of their remarkable contributions echoes throughout the book. One of war's many unfortunate ironies is that a worthy army can be betrayed by incompetent leadership, and Catton makes a strong case for just that reality in his examination of the Army of the Potomac.</span>
  <a data-text-id="8134980866329431246" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


      <div class="reviewFooter uitext buttons">
          

