<div id="review_3430879900" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3430879900" />
    <a title="Christopher B" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/53375929-christopher-b"><img alt="Christopher B" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1537371911p2/53375929.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3430879900?book_show_action=true">Jul 21, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Christopher B" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Christopher B" href="/user/show/53375929-christopher-b">Christopher B</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3430879900" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer3701530542121697073">This was one of the best written books I’ve ever read, history or not. For a book written 60 years ago, it feels refreshingly modern. Catton’s writing manages to be casual while still being chock full of interesting facts. His writing also verges on poetic at times. Here’s a passage discussing the night before the beginning of the Battle of Antietam, the single bloodiest day of the war: <br/><br/>“And while they slept the lazy, rainy breeze drifted through the East Wood and the West Wood and the cornfield</span>
  <span id="freeText3701530542121697073" style="display:none">This was one of the best written books I’ve ever read, history or not. For a book written 60 years ago, it feels refreshingly modern. Catton’s writing manages to be casual while still being chock full of interesting facts. His writing also verges on poetic at times. Here’s a passage discussing the night before the beginning of the Battle of Antietam, the single bloodiest day of the war: <br /><br />“And while they slept the lazy, rainy breeze drifted through the East Wood and the West Wood and the cornfield, and riffled over the copings of the stone bridge to the south, touching them for the last time before dead men made them famous. The flags were all furled and the bugles stilled, and the hot metal of the guns on the ridges had cooled, and the army was asleep—tenting tonight on the old camp ground, with never a song to cheer because the voices that might sing it were all stilled on this most crowded and most lonely of fields. And whatever it may be that nerves men to die for a flag or a phrase or a man or an inexpressible dream was drowsing with them, ready to wake with the dawn.” <br /><br />This book is highly recommended and I can’t wait to read the rest of the series. </span>
  <a data-text-id="3701530542121697073" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


