<div id="review_2759919773" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/2759919773" />
    <a title="Ralph Gardner" class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/46031455-ralph-gardner"><img alt="Ralph Gardner" src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1439764404p2/46031455.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/2759919773?book_show_action=true">Mar 22, 2019</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Ralph Gardner" class="user" itemprop="url" name="Ralph Gardner" href="/user/show/46031455-ralph-gardner">Ralph Gardner</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="it was amazing"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">it was amazing</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span></span>

          <span class="greyText">&nbsp;&middot;&nbsp;</span>
          <a class="lightGreyText" title="Kindle Edition " href="/book/show/38824705-mr-lincoln-s-army">review of another edition</a>


        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer2759919773" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer11181447589566950115"><strong>Bruce Catton&apos;s &quot;Army of the Potomac&quot; Trilogy</strong><br/><br/>&quot;Mr. Lincoln&apos;s Army&quot; - &quot;Glory Road&quot; - &quot;A Stillness at Appomattox&quot;<br/>I have read these books at least 6 times since I first saw them in the early 1960s and never tire of this prose. I have since then found books by other authors that belong in the same league - but Bruce Catton to me still reigns supreme. I am especially moved whenever I read the last pages of the middle volume, as Lincoln prepares to speak at Gettysburg in Nov 1863 - and the masterful way</span>
  <span id="freeText11181447589566950115" style="display:none"><strong>Bruce Catton's "Army of the Potomac" Trilogy</strong><br /><br />"Mr. Lincoln's Army" - "Glory Road" - "A Stillness at Appomattox"<br />I have read these books at least 6 times since I first saw them in the early 1960s and never tire of this prose. I have since then found books by other authors that belong in the same league - but Bruce Catton to me still reigns supreme. I am especially moved whenever I read the last pages of the middle volume, as Lincoln prepares to speak at Gettysburg in Nov 1863 - and the masterful way Catton ends that volume just as Lincoln stands up to speak. I once read some pages from that chapter to a class of adult college students, and was gratified to see those words moved them as much as they moved me.<br />There is no other author so capable of enchanting us with our own history (although Barbara W. Tuchman is equally brilliant with her histories of other people). I recommend these books without hesitation and am glad they are now in ebook format. ( I wore out my hardcover book club editions of this trilogy more than 20 years ago!)</span>
  <a data-text-id="11181447589566950115" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


